If any table is not in BCNF, we will decompose it. Otherwise, we will justify why the current schema is already normalized. 2. Functional Dependencies & BCNF Verification 2.1 Applicant Table (applicant) Primary Key: applicant_id Functional Dependencies (FDs): applicant_id → {name, email, phone, resume, location} email → applicant_id (since email is UNIQUE) BCNF Check: Both applicant_id and email are superkeys. No partial or transitive dependencies exist. ✅ BCNF Compliant 2.2 Company Table (company) Primary Key: company_id Functional Dependencies: company_id → {name, industry, location, website} BCNF Check: No non-trivial FDs exist where the determinant is not a superkey. ✅ BCNF Compliant 2.3 Skill Table (skill) Primary Key: skill_id Functional Dependencies: skill_id → skill_name skill_name → skill_id (assuming skill names are unique) BCNF Check: Both skill_id and skill_name are candidate keys. ✅ BCNF Compliant 2.4 Category Table (category) Primary Key: category_id Functional Dependencies: category_id → category_name category_name → category_id (assuming category names are unique) BCNF Check: Both category_id and category_name are candidate keys. ✅ BCNF Compliant 2.5 Job Table (job) Primary Key: job_id Functional Dependencies: job_id → {title, description, location, salary, posted_date, company_id} company_id → name (but name is not in this table) BCNF Check: No partial or transitive dependencies. ✅ BCNF Compliant 2.6 Application Table (application) Primary Key: application_id Functional Dependencies: application_id → {applicant_id, job_id, application_date, status} {applicant_id, job_id} → application_id (assuming one application per job per applicant) BCNF Check: application_id is the primary key. The composite {applicant_id, job_id} could also be a candidate key. ✅ BCNF Compliant 2.7 Job_Skill Table (job_skill) Composite Key: {job_id, skill_id} Functional Dependencies: {job_id, skill_id} → {} (no non-key attributes) BCNF Check: No non-key attributes → automatically in BCNF. ✅ BCNF Compliant 2.8 Job_Category Table (job_category) Composite Key: {job_id, category_id} Functional Dependencies: {job_id, category_id} → {} (no non-key attributes) BCNF Check: No non-key attributes → automatically in BCNF. ✅ BCNF Compliant 3. Schema Improvements (Recommendations) While all tables are in BCNF, some improvements can enhance data integrity: 3.1 Change salary to numeric (Job Table) sql ALTER TABLE job ALTER COLUMN salary TYPE numeric; ALTER TABLE job ADD CHECK (salary >= 0); 3.2 Add ENUM or CHECK for status (Application Table) sql ALTER TABLE application ADD CONSTRAINT status_check CHECK (status IN ('Pending', 'Accepted', 'Rejected')); 3.3 Set Default Dates sql ALTER TABLE job ALTER COLUMN posted_date SET DEFAULT CURRENT_DATE; ALTER TABLE application ALTER COLUMN application_date SET DEFAULT CURRENT_DATE; 4. Conclusion All tables are in BCNF because: Every determinant is a superkey (either primary or candidate key). No partial or transitive dependencies exist. No decomposition needed since the schema is already normalized. Minor improvements recommended (e.g., salary as numeric, status constraints). ✅ Final Schema is BCNF Compliant. For your job portal database, these are likely performance bottlenecks when scaling:

  • Slow job searches (especially when filtering by multiple criteria)

  • Application status tracking delays

2. Indexing Strategy Implementation

Recommended Indexes (add to your create.sql):

sql
Copy
Download
-- Core Search Performance
CREATE INDEX idx_job_composite ON job(title, location, salary);
CREATE INDEX idx_applicant_location ON applicant(location);
CREATE INDEX idx_company_industry ON company(industry);

-- Relationship Accelerators
CREATE INDEX idx_job_skill_skill ON job_skill(skill_id);
CREATE INDEX idx_applicant_skill_composite ON applicant_skill(applicant_id, skill_id);
CREATE INDEX idx_application_status ON application(status);

-- Full-Text Search (for job descriptions/resumes)
CREATE EXTENSION pg_trgm;
CREATE INDEX idx_job_description_search ON job USING gin(description gin_trgm_ops);
CREATE INDEX idx_applicant_resume_search ON applicant USING gin(resume gin_trgm_ops);

5. Performance Monitoring

Add these queries to identify bottlenecks:

sql
Copy
Download
-- Check cache hit rate (should be > 99%)
SELECT sum(heap_blks_read) as heap_read,
       sum(heap_blks_hit)  as heap_hit,
       (sum(heap_blks_hit) - sum(heap_blks_read)) / sum(heap_blks_hit) as ratio
FROM pg_statio_user_tables;

-- Find sequential scans (indicating missing indexes)
SELECT relname, seq_scan, seq_tup_read, 
       seq_tup_read/seq_scan as avg_tuples_per_scan
FROM pg_stat_user_tables 
WHERE seq_scan > 0
ORDER BY seq_tup_read DESC;

2. Sample Query Implementation

A. SELECT Queries (4+ types)

  1. Complex JOIN with GROUP BY (Job Analytics)

sql
Copy
Download
-- Count applications per job category
SELECT c.category_name, COUNT(a.application_id) AS application_count
FROM category c
JOIN job_category jc ON c.category_id = jc.category_id
JOIN job j ON jc.job_id = j.job_id
LEFT JOIN application a ON j.job_id = a.job_id
GROUP BY c.category_name
ORDER BY application_count DESC;

  1. Subquery (High-Paying Jobs)

sql
Copy
Download
-- Jobs paying above average salary
SELECT j.title, c.name AS company, j.salary
FROM job j
JOIN company c ON j.company_id = c.company_id
WHERE j.salary > (SELECT AVG(salary) FROM job)
ORDER BY j.salary DESC;

  1. Window Function (Applicant Ranking)

sql
Copy
Download
-- Rank applicants by number of skills
SELECT a.name, a.email, 
       COUNT(as.skill_id) AS skill_count,
       RANK() OVER (ORDER BY COUNT(as.skill_id) DESC) AS applicant_rank
FROM applicant a
LEFT JOIN applicant_skill as ON a.applicant_id = as.applicant_id
GROUP BY a.applicant_id
LIMIT 10;

  1. Full-Text Search (Job Descriptions)

Copy
Download

JOIN company c ON j.company_id = c.company_id

-- Delete applicants who haven't applied in 2+ years
DELETE FROM applicant

);

Task 10: Query Execution Analysis and Optimization

1. Identifying Problematic Queries

For your job portal database, we'll analyze three queries that likely need optimization:

Query 1: Complex Job Search with Multiple Filters

sql
Copy
Download
SELECT j.job_id, j.title, c.name AS company, j.salary
FROM job j
JOIN company c ON j.company_id = c.company_id
JOIN job_skill js ON j.job_id = js.job_id
JOIN skill s ON js.skill_id = s.skill_id
WHERE j.location = 'New York'
  AND s.skill_name IN ('Python', 'SQL', 'Java')
  AND j.salary BETWEEN 80000 AND 120000
  AND j.posted_date > CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL '30 days';

Query 2: Applicant Skill Matching

sql
Copy
Download
SELECT a.name, a.email, j.title, c.name AS company
FROM applicant a
JOIN applicant_skill aps ON a.applicant_id = aps.applicant_id
JOIN job_skill js ON aps.skill_id = js.skill_id
JOIN job j ON js.job_id = j.job_id
JOIN company c ON j.company_id = c.company_id
WHERE a.location = 'San Francisco'
  AND j.status = 'Active'
ORDER BY j.posted_date DESC;

Query 3: Company Dashboard Analytics

sql
Copy
Download
SELECT 
  j.title,
  COUNT(a.application_id) AS total_applications,
  SUM(CASE WHEN a.status = 'Accepted' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS accepted,
  SUM(CASE WHEN a.status = 'Rejected' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS rejected,
  (SELECT AVG(salary) FROM job WHERE company_id = 123) AS company_avg_salary
FROM job j
LEFT JOIN application a ON j.job_id = a.job_id
WHERE j.company_id = 123
GROUP BY j.job_id, j.title;

Typical Problems Found:

  • Sequential scans on large tables

  • Missing composite indexes for common filter combinations

  • Inefficient join strategies

3. Optimization Strategies

Optimization for Query 1:

sql
Copy
Download
-- Create targeted composite index
CREATE INDEX idx_job_search ON job(location, salary, posted_date) 
INCLUDE (title, company_id);

-- Add index for skill filtering
CREATE INDEX idx_job_skill_filter ON job_skill(skill_id) 
INCLUDE (job_id);

-- Rewrite query with CTE for better planning
WITH skill_filter AS (
  SELECT DISTINCT js.job_id
  FROM job_skill js
  JOIN skill s ON js.skill_id = s.skill_id
  WHERE s.skill_name IN ('Python', 'SQL', 'Java')
)
SELECT j.job_id, j.title, c.name AS company, j.salary
FROM job j
JOIN company c ON j.company_id = c.company_id
JOIN skill_filter sf ON j.job_id = sf.job_id
WHERE j.location = 'New York'
  AND j.salary BETWEEN 80000 AND 120000
  AND j.posted_date > CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL '30 days';

Optimization for Query 2 (Applicant Matching):

sql
Copy
Download
-- Create covering index for applicant location
CREATE INDEX idx_applicant_location ON applicant(location) 
INCLUDE (name, email);

-- Improve join performance
CREATE INDEX idx_applicant_skill_join ON applicant_skill(applicant_id, skill_id);
CREATE INDEX idx_job_skill_join ON job_skill(skill_id, job_id);

-- Add partial index for active jobs
CREATE INDEX idx_job_active ON job(job_id) 
WHERE status = 'Active';

Optimization for Query 3 (Company Dashboard):

sql
Copy
Download
-- Create function-based index for status counts
CREATE INDEX idx_application_status_counts ON application(job_id, status);

-- Materialized view for company analytics
CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW mv_company_stats AS
SELECT 
  j.company_id,
  j.job_id,
  j.title,
  COUNT(a.application_id) AS total_applications,
  COUNT(a.status) FILTER (WHERE a.status = 'Accepted') AS accepted,
  COUNT(a.status) FILTER (WHERE a.status = 'Rejected') AS rejected
FROM job j
LEFT JOIN application a ON j.job_id = a.job_id
GROUP BY j.company_id, j.job_id, j.title;

-- Refresh schedule (daily)
REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW mv_company_stats;

Implementing the Bonus Task with Streamlit

Yes, you can absolutely use Streamlit to build your job portal website for the bonus task! Streamlit is an excellent choice because:

  1. Python-based - Works well with your PostgreSQL database (via psycopg2 or SQLAlchemy)

  2. Rapid development - Create interactive web apps with minimal code

  3. Visualization support - Built-in charting for query results

  4. Deployment friendly - Easy to host on Streamlit Cloud, Heroku, or other platforms

import streamlit as st
import psycopg2
from config.db_config import DB_PARAMS  # Store credentials securely

# Initialize connection
@st.cache_resource
def init_connection():
    return psycopg2.connect(**DB_PARAMS)

conn = init_connection()

# Page setup
st.set_page_config(page_title="Job Portal", layout="wide")
st.title("Job Portal Dashboard")

# Navigation
page = st.sidebar.selectbox("Choose a page", 
    ["Job Search", "Applicant Analytics", "Company Portal"])

if page == "Job Search":
    st.header("Find Your Dream Job")
    
    # Search filters
    col1, col2, col3 = st.columns(3)
    with col1:
        location = st.selectbox("Location", ["All"] + get_locations(conn))
    with col2:
        salary_range = st.slider("Salary Range", 0, 200000, (50000, 120000))
    with col3:
        skills = st.multiselect("Skills", get_skills(conn))
    
    # Execute and display query
    if st.button("Search Jobs"):
        jobs = search_jobs(conn, location, salary_range, skills)
        st.dataframe(jobs)
        
        # Visualization
        st.bar_chart(jobs.groupby('company')['salary'].mean())

elif page == "Applicant Analytics":
    st.header("Applicant Statistics")
    # Implement other pages similarly...

# Helper functions
def search_jobs(conn, location, salary_range, skills):
    query = """
    SELECT j.title, c.name as company, j.location, j.salary 
    FROM job j JOIN company c ON j.company_id = c.company_id
    WHERE j.salary BETWEEN %s AND %s
    """
    params = [salary_range[0], salary_range[1]]
    
    if location != "All":
        query += " AND j.location = %s"
        params.append(location)
    
    if skills:
        query += """
        AND j.job_id IN (
            SELECT js.job_id FROM job_skill js
            JOIN skill s ON js.skill_id = s.skill_id
            WHERE s.skill_name = ANY(%s)
        )
        """
        params.append(skills)
    
    with conn.cursor() as cur:
        cur.execute(query, params)
        columns = [desc[0] for desc in cur.description]
        return pd.DataFrame(cur.fetchall(), columns=columns)
